One of my favorite parts of our home is the kitchen. It was all styled around the kitchen island which I sourced off Craigslist. We needed such a long and narrow island to fit in the space and we also wanted it to be tall so the best option I found was a guys old work bench. However, the only problem was that the work bench was actually counter height instead of bar height so naturally I decided to source antique 2x4’s on Craigslist. After digging through a guys truck bed I found four that matched the age of the work bench and I added them on to the table to get the height that we wanted. (Wow i had a lot of time on my hands during the pandemic lol)
Home sweet home 😊 also I HAVE A question for y’all in my story, please help.

Saw some really amazing works but my all time favorite was this embroidered piece by Jordan Nassar. 

:://:://><:://:://><:://:://><:://:://><:://:://><

Each recent work begins with Nassar creating a composition out of these patterns, sections of which he designates for the landscapes. He then sends this work to women in the Hebron region of Palestine who embroider the patterns in colors of their choice, sending them back to Nassar, who responds to their choices in his renderings of the landscapes. As such, two cultures coincide in Nassar’s canvases. The longstanding familial, matrilineal transmission of the embroidery tradition in Palestine with the Western, painterly impulses of Nassar’s upbringing and context as a diaspora Palestinian living in New York.

Inspiration these day…. But also burnout. Caption below ❤️

This past year I’ve felt so burnt out to design anything new but I finally feel like I’m turning the corner and working on some ideas I actually want to share and sell. 

I think having a brand has put a lot of pressure on myself as a designer that everything has to be good enough and perfect if it’s going to be sold. 

I’m realizing that it’s okay to design and create collection m that every might not love.

With that, there is such a  balance between sharing my vision of design and also making it approachable to other people (cost approachable and design approachable)

Anyway, lots to think about but I’m excited about a couple ideas I have up my sleeve.

Playing with color. Getting the gears turning on some up coming color selections. While I love to play with fabrics and paint decks these tile samples are proving to be perfect to playing around with what color combinations I love and don’t love. ❤️

@heathceramics

(A magical weekend where I happened to pack all green outfits-again, he knows me so well)

The Ambrose club Sofa set is hand stuffed quilted upholstery that features a soft cushion and modular seat back. The set can be perfectly pieced together to feature a love seat or separated  to create two comfy lounge chairs. 

What I love about designing heirloom furniture and lighting is that these pieces are made to last a life time. You see this in the construction of this sofa which features hand tied springs . 

My goal has always been to promote slow fashion, and the same can be said about slow furniture. Stop buying mass produced cheap stuff!!!!

We feel so lucky to have celebrated our wedding surrounded by our closest friends and loving family in the landscape that I hold dearest to my heart. It was truly a dream. 

Months (and months and months and months) of planning went into having a wedding off the grid and we felt a little crazy hosting the ceremony and reception at The Cabin which is over a century old and has no electricity (except a Honda generator) and no running water, but it all worked out beyond our wildest expectations. 

From picking flowers for my bouquet with my mother and grandmother the morning of the wedding to embroidering each guests name on their dinner napkin- each little detail and every special moments from the weekend will forever fill my heart with joy. 

And thank you Griffin for the incredible dinner and also for pushing the Land Cruiser when it got stuck in the middle of the road.

What are your hobbies? How are they different from your job? My sister and I were talking about how much better it is to ask someone about their hobbies instead of “what they do for work”. Obviously a lot of people love their job and identify in their career (me) but i bet you get to know someone a lot better from their hobbies than their job. Anyway, I wanted to share a little about my life outside of my work and I want to hear about you !!! 

- okay why is Disney Land actually the happiest place ever? I went into it with no expectations and when I say I was beaming all day it’s not even an exaggeration, and we were there 14 hours. This is not a hobby but I do love a good theme park. 

- I love learning about new artists and hearing about their journey, where they were born , why their style is the way that it is- I find it fascinating how life influences an artists creations. 

-tbh I peaked during Covid when I started growing my own veggies.

- skiing > anything else ever 

- I could talk about the struggles of building a wardrobe I like for hours and I have a deep appreciate for friends who go to dinner with me and can also talk about their clothing struggles lol because I dress like a 12 year old school boy on a good day. 

- I am still convinced I can run 27 miles on my 27th birthday. 

- while climbing a 14ner is not really ever fun, when you get to the top there is really nothing like it. It’s been a couple years since I’ve hiked one but it’s on the list for maybe the end of this summer or next <3

- my husband is my best friend and we are always scheming and dreaming and I can’t wait to share a little design we are working on 

- I collect rocks and I don’t know why. But I always have and I can’t seem to stop and idk what to do with all them

I started my business three and a half years ago. I had so many designs ready to go while some I spent months prototyping. From there I launched my first collection 6 months later. Thanks in huge part to @vhs.ventures , @interiordecline and @leibal for taking me under their wings and truly helping me launch into the design world. 
Since then it’s been a roller coaster of having jobs, getting fired (job dissolved), getting other jobs- anything to support the dream of having this business and learn as much as I possibly can. I feel like I finally am standing on two feet. And not just sketching on a little desk in my living room :) I  am so excited to share more from some upcoming projects that I’m working on right now, but until then thank you all for your love and support. ❤️ the point of this post is to also say I got a studio lol yay. Cheers to a new ~era~
Frank Lloyd Wright ✨ Lil slice of heaven. ✨

I’ve been wanting a pendant light like this for so long. It’s an Elegant Vintage Art Deco Murano Chandelier attributed to Barovier Toso, made in Italy in 1930s. Handwork of blown glass masters. Exquisite detail in the glass shade in Murano glass, I honestly can’t believe the details now that I’m seeing it in person. The glass lampshade is made in the shape of a sculptural flower, which gives a soft glow. Exquisite brass details complement the elegant elements of the lamp. My favorite is knowing that it’s full of antique Italian craftsmanship. Can’t wait for you all to see it installed. ✨💗✨

Continuing on our theme of #delulu Some of you probably know this but the entire reason i started to design and sell furniture and lighting was because I was sick of seeing furniture be poorly made, used for a couple years and then thrown into the landfill. It was really important for me to design heirloom quality pieces that were made to last several generation. While each piece is timeless in their craft and style I always hope to keep an item exciting and youthful.

Five years ago I studied how furniture could become invaluable heirlooms that people would eventually pass down to future generations. I was enamored with the idea that when a piece of furniture is well made people can use it everyday and it functions with no problems therefore allowing the individuals to interact with the piece, create memories and eventually pass it down to other loved ones in their family. It’s an endless circle that all starts with quality made furniture which is the pillar of Lulu LaFortune Limited ❤️

Some of my favorite lil Polaroid snaps from the wedding ✨❤️✨The wedding weekend was so perfect that we ended up deciding to just stay at the cabin for another week. We caught our dinners, swam in the river, sat and watched the hummingbirds. Really just took in the beauty of the environment around us and the immense love we felt being surrounded by our friends and family for the best weekend ever. It was so special and these little pics always remind me of those little memories ❤️

Our next #BetterWithAge episode features Lulu Lafortune @lulu.lafortune – a Furniture Designer based in LA who, before starting her brand, worked with notable designers such as Kelly Wearstler and James Perse. Her designs have been featured in Vogue, Architectural Digest, and more.⁠
⁠
After graduating from SCAD, Lulu was intentional about finding a role that doesn’t contribute to the wasteful fast furniture industry. Her namesake brand is dedicated to creating durable, bold, and cheerful heirloom pieces that will last for generations. While her home style is simple and practical, Lulu’s work is more decorative. Still, functionality is vital to Lulu’s overall aesthetic because she believes that functional pieces built with integrity will be cherished and passed on. ⁠

Do you guys agree?? So curious what your thoughts are on this. 

Are we in the eta of the last great estate sales? 

It feels like there is a going to be a big gap until the next one as there have been a couple generations less interested in truly investing in items for their home. 

To me the generation currently leaving their homes are the ones that really cared about their belongings and investing in really well made furniture and objects. 

But it’s not just the buyer it’s also the retailers at that time we’re just less about trends and more about well made items. But  I do think we are  going to see a gap of time before truly start filling their homes with timeless treasure.
